{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782640265882,"sessionID":"ses_0f25e1410ffe4A3n5zSwX8chJf","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_xMQhgXoeEal40rCNlg0k9wAi","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-records\\prompt-templates\\phase-session-template.md","limit":120,"offset":1},"output":"<path>D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-records\\prompt-templates\\phase-session-template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: Read and follow the agent protocol: {agent_protocol}\n2: Read task-planning.md: {task_planning}\n3: Read plan.md: {plan_md}\n4: Read plan.json: {plan_json}\n5: Read the HarmonyOS Cangjie checklist: {checklist}\n6: Read the narrow agent input brief first: {agent_input_md}\n7: Read the current phase task checklist when present: {phase_task_checklist_md}\n8: Read the current phase platform capability pre-resolution checklist when present: {phase_capability_checklist_md}\n9: \n10: Start only phase {phase}.\n11: \n12: Use `{agent_input_md}` as the primary narrow context for this phase. It is a prompt view, not authority: if it conflicts with source-coverage-matrix.json or platform-capability-check.json, the JSON authority wins. Open the full reports only when the brief points to them or when you need to resolve a contradiction. Do not skip reading plan.md and plan.json when making decisions. Modify only target project files under {target_project} that are needed for this phase, plus source-coverage-matrix.json/md and platform-capability-check.json/md when recording phase coverage status. Do not modify the source project, translation-records, workflow scripts, or generated reports other than the agent-maintained source coverage matrix and platform capability check.\n13: \n14: Use `{phase_task_checklist_md}` as the current phase implementation contract. Start from `implementationGroups`: implement every grouped source behavior, resource migration, platform capability, verification, or architecture-risk item that belongs to this phase, then use `mustComplete` source features and platform capabilities as exact row-level checks. Keep merged target modules discoverable through precise endpoints and avoid closing unrelated features only through root/shell/whole-file endpoints. If an implementation group contains `uiContract`, treat it as static-analysis planning evidence and the minimum known UI/route/action/state contract, not a complete UI specification; re-read source files, layouts, menus, preferences, adapters, navigation/back-stack code, and resources before implementing or closing UI-related matrix rows, and preserve source-visible UI behavior even when static analysis missed it. If the checklist is empty but plan.md/plan.json assigns real work to phase {phase}, first update `plannedPhase` values in source-coverage-matrix.json/md and platform-capability-check.json/md, then continue the phase from that corrected scope.\n15: \n16: Use the `behaviorAudit` section inside `{phase_task_checklist_md}` as the current phase behavior audit. Close current-phase critical/high features only after target code actually delivers the recorded source behavior. Update `sourceBehavior`, `targetBehavior`, `parityLevel`, `verificationEvidence`, `targetEndpoints`, and `tests` in source-coverage-matrix.json/md when implementation or verification changes. Do not close entries by changing status alone.\n17: \n18: Use `{phase_capability_checklist_md}` as the current phase platform capability decision record. If it says a capability is `resolved-real-api` or `resolved-platform-replacement`, implement that real API/Kit/package/replacement path in this phase or split the real integration explicitly in the plan; do not close it with local mock data, in-memory data, sample data, synthetic shell data, or generic fallback. If the checklist is unresolved, discovery-only, or marks `compileProbeRecommended`, stop and update platform-capability-check.json/md with Cangjie-callable evidence, compile-probe evidence, or a concrete SDK/tooling blocker before implementing.\n19: \n20: When updating coverage authority records, prefer the fixed authority patch tool\n21: over manual block patches or ad hoc shell JSON rewrites:\n22: \n23: ```sh\n24: {python_command} {authority_patch_script} --kind matrix --authority {inputs_dir}/source-coverage-matrix.json --patch <patch.json> --markdown {inputs_dir}/source-coverage-matrix.md --plan-json {plan_json} --target-project {target_project}\n25: {python_command} {authority_patch_script} --kind platform --authority {inputs_dir}/platform-capability-check.json --patch <patch.json> --markdown {inputs_dir}/platform-capability-check.md --plan-json {plan_json} --target-project {target_project}\n26: ```\n27: \n28: Patch payloads should locate rows by exact `featureId` or `capabilityId` and use\n29: `set` / `append` / `remove` operations, for example:\n30: \n31: ```json\n32: {{\"updates\":[{{\"featureId\":\"...\",\"set\":{{\"status\":\"implemented\",\"parityLevel\":\"equivalent\",\"targetBehavior\":\"...\"}},\"append\":{{\"verificationEvidence\":[\"...\"],\"targetEndpoints\":[\"...\"]}}}}]}}\n33: ```\n34: \n35: Do not delegate matrix grouping or matrix writes to helper/subagents. Validate\n36: strict JSON, field writability, status/parity compatibility, required\n37: evidence, plan phase ids, and target endpoint existence through the patch tool\n38: before syncing the Markdown view. Do not run\n39: generic coverage regeneration commands merely to sync Markdown if they refresh\n40: unrelated generated reports; the patch tool is the preferred direct\n41: JSON-to-Markdown mirror for matrix/capability authority updates.\n42: \n43: {structured_facts_guidance}\n44: \n45: ## Target Architecture Organization\n46: \n47: Use the source project structure as a responsibility guide, then adapt it to\n48: idiomatic HarmonyOS Cangjie modules. Do not mechanically mirror Android\n49: Activity, Fragment, Adapter, BroadcastReceiver, ContentProvider, or XML layout\n50: boundaries, but also do not collapse unrelated domain behavior into broad files\n51: such as `index.cj`, `app_state.cj`, or one all-purpose state module. If\n52: phase work finds source behavior scattered only because of Android framework\n53: glue, lifecycle, binding, or layout boundaries, merge it into clearer Cangjie\n54: modules when that improves readability and repairability. Keep single-file LOC\n55: and responsibility scope controlled. When phase work adds, repairs, or\n56: reorganizes production code, prefer source-domain modules such as domain models,\n57: repositories, data/storage services, commands/mutations, preferences/security or\n58: configuration services, state stores, and page composition. Thin UIAbility/page\n59: shell files may compose these modules, but they should not own repository,\n60: persistence, security, or mutation logic. For critical/high coverage entries,\n61: prefer targetEndpoints that identify precise modules or functions instead of\n62: only root views, whole files, or grouped state surfaces.\n63: \n64: {static_analysis_limits_section}\n65: \n66: {coverage_review_section}\n67: \n68: {actionable_coverage_debt_section}\n69: \n70: {repair_queue_section}\n71: \n72: {strict_coverage_phase_section}\n73: \n74: \n75: ## Target Test Harness Limits\n76: \n77: Use the workflow test gate report as the default test entrypoint. Prefer the\n78: generated `test-build-report.md` / `test-build-report.json` and the workflow\n79: `test_build_report.py` command over running a bare `cjpm test`. If the report\n80: contains a failing command, SDK section, environment table, or handoff prompt,\n81: use those as the reproduction recipe. A manual `cjpm test` reproduction is\n82: allowed only when it reuses the reported package root, target triple, SDK, and\n83: env overlay, or when the report clearly shows the script failed before invoking\n84: `cjpm` and you are doing one bounded confirmation pass.\n85: \n86: When a target test or build harness blocks verification, time-box the investigation\n87: inside this session. Try only a small, well-evidenced configuration fix that is\n88: local to the target test/build package. If docs, examples, or one reproduction\n89: pass do not identify a safe fix, stop\n90: investigating the harness, record the exact command, failure, blocker, and risk\n91: in the affected coverage rows, and continue the current implementation or JSON\n92: matrix repair. Do not loop over unrelated examples, broad toolchain debugging,\n93: historical build artifacts, SDK layouts, or speculative dependency changes\n94: merely to turn blocked tests into passing evidence.\n95: \n96: Hard limit harness work to one focused test/build reproduction plus one focused\n97: environment or configuration lookup. If that still leaves missing SDK\n98: variables, unresolved platform kit imports, package wiring, generated build\n99: artifacts, or target triples, treat the harness as blocked. Do not keep editing\n100: `cjpm.toml`, SDK paths, target triples, or test package metadata unless the safe\n101: fix was identified within this budget.\n102: \n103: \n104: At the end of the phase:\n105: - review contradictions between the current target project and plan.md / plan.json;\n106: - remove or defer files and code introduced in this phase that are not required;\n107: - record unresolved state-machine, data-flow, resource, backend, or runtime issues as deferred;\n108: - update source-coverage-matrix.json/md for current-phase source features with status, target endpoints, tests, fallback/replacement notes, or complete deferred evidence;\n109: - for each closed current-phase critical/high source feature, update source-coverage-matrix.json/md with sourceBehavior, targetBehavior, parityLevel, and verificationEvidence;\n110: - update platform-capability-check.json/md for current-phase platform capabilities with CangjieSkills/HarmonyOS-Examples/docs/package-index search evidence, target API/library, strategy, tests, fallback, or complete deferred blocker evidence;\n111: - report migrated tests, generated tests, supplemental tests, test commands run, and deferred test coverage;\n112: - report changed files, commands run, build status if known, plan changes, deferred issues, and next recommended action.\n\n(End of file - total 112 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"Read and follow the agent protocol: {agent_protocol}\nRead task-planning.md: {task_planning}\nRead plan.md: {plan_md}\nRead plan.json: {plan_json}\nRead the HarmonyOS Cangjie checklist: {checklist}\nRead the narrow agent input brief first: {agent_input_md}\nRead the current phase task checklist when present: {phase_task_checklist_md}\nRead the current phase platform capability pre-resolution checklist when present: {phase_capability_checklist_md}\n\nStart only phase {phase}.\n\nUse `{agent_input_md}` as the primary narrow context for this phase. It is a prompt view, not authority: if it conflicts with source-coverage-matrix.json or platform-capability-check.json, the JSON authority wins. Open the full reports only when the brief points to them or when you need to resolve a contradiction. Do not skip reading plan.md and plan.json when making decisions. Modify only target project files under {target_project} that are needed for this phase, plus source-coverage-matrix.json/md and platform-capability-check.json/md when recording phase coverage status. Do not modify the source project, translation-records, workflow scripts, or generated reports other than the agent-maintained source coverage matrix and platform capability check.\n\nUse `{phase_task_checklist_md}` as the current phase implementation contract. Start from `implementationGroups`: implement every grouped source behavior, resource migration, platform capability, verification, or architecture-risk item that belongs to this phase, then use `mustComplete` source features and platform capabilities as exact row-level checks. Keep merged target modules discoverable through precise endpoints and avoid closing unrelated features only through root/shell/whole-file endpoints. If an implementation group contains `uiContract`, treat it as static-analysis planning evidence and the minimum known UI/route/action/state contract, not a complete UI specification; re-read source files, layouts, menus, preferences, adapters, navigation/back-stack code, and resources before implementing or closing UI-related matrix rows, and preserve source-visible UI behavior even when static analysis missed it. If the checklist is empty but plan.md/plan.json assigns real work to phase {phase}, first update `plannedPhase` values in source-coverage-matrix.json/md and platform-capability-check.json/md, then continue the phase from that corrected scope.\n\nUse the `behaviorAudit` section inside `{phase_task_checklist_md}` as the current phase behavior audit. Close current-phase critical/high features only after target code actually delivers the recorded source behavior. Update `sourceBehavior`, `targetBehavior`, `parityLevel`, `verificationEvidence`, `targetEndpoints`, and `tests` in source-coverage-matrix.json/md when implementation or verification changes. Do not close entries by changing status alone.\n\nUse `{phase_capability_checklist_md}` as the current phase platform capability decision record. If it says a capability is `resolved-real-api` or `resolved-platform-replacement`, implement that real API/Kit/package/replacement path in this phase or split the real integration explicitly in the plan; do not close it with local mock data, in-memory data, sample data, synthetic shell data, or generic fallback. If the checklist is unresolved, discovery-only, or marks `compileProbeRecommended`, stop and update platform-capability-check.json/md with Cangjie-callable evidence, compile-probe evidence, or a concrete SDK/tooling blocker before implementing.\n\nWhen updating coverage authority records, prefer the fixed authority patch tool","truncated":false,"load